\begin_layout Standard
Section - Of the Sun and Moon
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is perhaps te granddaddy of what is problematic about the book.
 The whole teleport-into-the-inner-shell affair.
 Okay, I get the lush greenery, ample light and so on.
 Why no fauna? Perhaps the place is not that old.
 Okay, let's accept that.
 On the more pragmatic side, there's this duality with the suns and the
 sun.
 The references get mixed up.
 Sometimes they talk about the suns, as if the hadn't noticed it was just
 one.
 Sometimes they talk about the sun - I think.
 that crucial key difference is lost somewhere in the text.
 The reader, as well as the heroes, should definitely be puzzled at what
 they are actually seeing.
 there's a small get-out-of-jail clause, because of the apparent brightness
 of the binary (the two suns), which most of the time looks like a single
 sun (the orbit of the second one of the binary is too small).
 The problem is, the reader doesn't know about that, or that we are in Algol.
 I can only accept, that in good faith, he believes there's some explanation
 that he can either extrapolate (indeed he could, but I don't know how difficult
 it could prove), or that I can reveal later on.
 Though in the book, it's a messed up affair.
 Also, I have a porblem with the length or rather the slow action of the
 section, and the lack of development between the chars.
 They each seem to develop, but as an interior process, not through dialogue,
 at least not as much as i believe they should.
 About the jungle parts, I saw bear Gryll do worse stuff, so I'm happy with
 them mostly.
\end_layout

