 still clings on what seems for him to be the only way.
 Generally, one of the best sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Section - The game board
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I like the section, though I believe the main problem lies in the description
 of the 'workshop'/shipyard as well as the confrontation between the Patriarch
 and hilderich and ron - which is the major plot.
 Perhaps it's fine, perhaps it's not.
 I sided on the dumbstruck and completely caught by surprise part that leaves
 the both of them just listening to him.
 The fact that he spills the beans seemed logical if he had been denied
 victory for thousands of years.
 The frustration would have normally been unbearable.
 Other than that, it's kind of ignominious how Amonas exits the novel alltogethe
r like a puppet, and the player tank is kind of dull.
 Supposedly I wanted it to contrast itself with the tower/spaceship of Agrippa,
 which was modeled like a french aristocrat's study or something like that.
 Other than stylistic problems with that, the plot revealed in itself stands
 for a different discussion alltogether.
 I find it generally thin at best, but intriguing and marvellously sinister
 and long term.
 Something like that could happen and it's not just the limitation and the
 logic errors of the computer/AI, or the genetic markers, and the soil and
 the whole continent and so on, stuff that I should have made more room
 to further explain, perhaps from Perconals/The Waking Man's view.
 The problem is it's a hasty explanation, somethingthat perhaps indeed the
 patriarch could hav ewritten himself, bu the main problem lies in the fact
 that it's not very cohesive, and there seem to be holes riddled throughout..
 If one can take everything in good faith, in the same awestruck fashion
 as Hilderich, then it's fine, though I believe most will simply try and
 read through the mass of Patriarch's ramblings into the next pages, and
 perhaps shuffle back and forth when the book's done to try and make sense
 of it.
 A problematic section that though the heart of the plot connections, doesn't
 seem to carry them along as it should.
 Not the splashing near-ending I had in mind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Section - Homeward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I almost wrote this on the fly.
 I really wanted to put an ending to the story, and I had to cramm in together
 Celia and Perconal.
 Generally Celia pops out on various section, becuase I couldn't afford
 her more pages, but I think she's a nice secondary char.
 On to the problems with this one, is that the retired/almost given up Perconal/
Jester/Waking Man, seems strangely disaffected by everything and all around
 him.
 No explanation about his whereabouts before hand and afterwards, his part
 of the plan and so on.
 Generally not a very good picture of the adversary of the patriarch.
 The suddenness of the patriarch's swapping (which happened on the previous
 section but is now shown how it affected the real life world) and the ensuing
 'I'm done for, pop her in the life boat as a sorry-I-messed-your-world'
 is too hasty for comfort.
 Naturally that's the whole problem with the book, that it seems like it
 was cut short, or was too long where it shouldn't be, all in all that it
 was uneven.
 Same thing goes for the Pilgrim's 'John Rambo' style, though I can picture
 it in a different light, something like a retelling from an epic story
 or something like that.
 A distant view , where everything happened too quickly, and what really
 mattered was that God's plan, according to the Pilgrim had come through,
 and he had served his purpose, dying a contend man.
 In more technical terms, the first part is subpar, while the latter, even
 though short, is to the point and could be worse.
 In all, not a very fitting end.
 
\end_layout

